Navigation

Navigation shows you how to get from one place to another

Navigation finds a path between two points in 3D space, avoiding any obstacles in its path.

It’s ideal for creating AI that considers its surroundings while hunting for a target. Some examples are enemies chasing the player or army units that avoid hazards as they move into position.

Navigation has some shortcomings that Godot 4.0 is due to fix, but it works as a quick and straightforward solution to pathfinding in Godot 3.x.

In this guide, you will learn how to:

  • Set up a Navigation node.
  • Create simple pathfinding.
  • Get chased by enemy AI.
  • Avoid locked doors.
  • Set up grid-based movement.

Setting up Navigation

Every Navigation node needs to have a child NavigationMeshInstance before it can find paths. This child holds a NavigationMesh resource, which defines the space available for points and paths.

To generate a NavigationMesh, you first need to add a new NavigationMesh resource to the NavigationMeshInstance and configure which parts of the scene to include in the Navigation under the Geometry subsection.

You can configure the NavigationMesh to generate the mesh based on Mesh Instances, Static Colliders, or both. With the Source Geometry Mode property, you can choose whether the mesh is based on node children of the NavigationMesh or nodes with a specific Group set.

Now, you can use the Bake NavMesh button at the top of the viewport and see the generated NavigationMesh. You can further fine-tune the baking by adjusting the other parameters in the NavigationMeshInstance. You can set the Max Slope in the Agent sub-category to control how steep the mesh can be before it blocks an agent from traversing it. The Height and Radius options let you control what the minimum amount of space an agent needs to traverse a part of the level.

Navigation’s key features

Find target locations with get_closest_point()

If you pass a position to this function, it returns the closest valid point on the NavigationMesh. This function is essential if you have two navigation meshes and want a body to navigate from one to another, or to ensure your AI won’t go out of bounds.

Find paths with get_simple_path()

This function is what makes Navigation so helpful. You pass in two points as parameters, where you want to navigate to and from on the NavigationMesh. The function finds the nearest points on the mesh and returns a PoolVector3Array path from the origin to the destination.

The get_simple_path() function has three parameters: a start position, an end position, and a Boolean called Optimize. Optimize is an optional parameter that merges points in a straight line, and it’s set to true by default.

The get_simple_path() function is far from perfect because it can return unoptimized paths. Godot 4.0 looks to fix these imperfections, but it gives decent results with a little tweaking for most situations.

Switch between NavigationMeshInstances with Enabled

The NavigationMeshInstance itself has a few key properties that help customize the area you want to navigate.

You can access and edit the NavigationMesh using the Navmesh property.

Also, you can enable or disable an entire NavigationMeshInstance with the Enabled property. A Navigation can use only one NavigationMeshInstance at a time, so we can change the shape by enabling one mesh and disabling the others.

How to use Navigation in practice

Now let’s look at some concrete use cases for Navigation.

Making enemies chase the player

Almost all games with enemies have some simple pathfinding behind their movement.

For example, Hotline Miami has enemies that rush you with baseball bats, while Civilization V has units moving from tile to tile. At its core, almost any game needs some simple form of pathfinding to avoid characters crashing into walls.

Navigation is the ideal node for this behavior in Godot. In the example below, we have an enemy character that chases the player.

We use a GridMap to make the floor and obstacles and bake a NavigationMesh to calculate the navigation space.

Our scene tree ends looking like this. Note that the GridMap is a child of NavigationMeshInstance, since we use the default configuration, where the children of the NavigationMeshInstance are used for baking the NavigationMesh.

Our navigation enemy uses a typical KinematicBody setup.

Our enemy needs a reference to the Navigation node and the target it’s following: in this case, our player.

onready var _model: Spatial = $Model
onready var _navigation: Navigation = get_node(navigation_path) as Navigation
onready var _player: Player3D = get_node(player_path) as Player3D

The algorithm for the navigation path is performance-intensive, so we use a frame counter variable to only look for a new path every tenth frame.

const FRAMES_BETWEEN_UPDATES := 10

func _physics_process(delta: float) -> void:
    if _frame_counter == 0:
        # We attempt to get a path from the enemy to the player.
        var potential_path = _navigation.get_simple_path(
            global_transform.origin, _player.global_transform.origin
        )
        # If the path array we get back is larger than 0 it's a valid path
        # and we assign it otherwise we stick to the old path.
        if potential_path.size() > 0:
            _path = potential_path
    _frame_counter = wrapi(_frame_counter + 1, 0, FRAMES_BETWEEN_UPDATES)

We now have a valid path to the player, but we need to remove points as the enemy arrives at them as we follow it.

    var position_on_navigation_mesh = _navigation.get_closest_point(global_transform.origin)

    # When we get close to the next point on the path, we remove that point
    if (
        position_on_navigation_mesh.distance_squared_to(_path[0]) < path_tolerance
        and _path.size() > 1
    ):
        _path.remove(0)

We find the direction to the next point and normalize it. We can then use it to orient the character model towards that direction. The _orient_character_to_direction() function calculates the rotation basis for the direction and uses the slerp() function to smoothly rotate the character towards this direction.

    var direction: Vector3 = _path[0] - position_on_navigation_mesh

    direction.y = 0.0
    direction = direction.normalized()

    _orient_character_to_direction(direction, delta)

func _orient_character_to_direction(direction: Vector3, delta: float) -> void:
    var left_axis := Vector3.UP.cross(direction)
    var rotation_basis := Basis(left_axis, Vector3.UP, direction)
    _model.transform.basis = _model.transform.basis.slerp(rotation_basis, delta * rotation_speed)

The final destination is the last point of the path. We use this to check if we have arrived at the endpoint. If we haven’t arrived yet, we calculate a velocity with linear_interpolate() and apply it to the KinematicBody with the move_and_slide_with_snap() function.

    var final_destination := _path[_path.size() - 1]

    if position_on_navigation_mesh.distance_squared_to(final_destination) > stopping_distance:
        _velocity = _velocity.linear_interpolate(direction * move_speed, acceleration * delta)
        _velocity = move_and_slide_with_snap(_velocity, _snap, Vector3.UP, true)

Note: The Path and PathFollow nodes pair excellently with the paths generated by a Navigation node. If you don’t want to move your characters towards points on a path manually, you can use these nodes instead, as laid out in the Path guide.

Making areas inaccessible with doors

It’s rare to have explorable worlds that don’t have some form of gate or door. In games like Resident Evil, different areas become available as you progress through the game, but certain enemies need to be able to follow you through doors once they’re unlocked.

One way to get enemies to respond to unlocked doors is to use a Navigation node with multiple NavigationMeshInstance children. You can switch between them using the Enabled property.

This method works well in simpler situations because the number of NavigationMeshInstance nodes increases exponentially with every locked door. With this approach, you also need code to handle the Enabled property for each NavigationMeshInstance.

For our example, we made two doors and one switch. The switch opens one door and closes the other. As a result, we only have two states to swap between, so we need two NavigationMeshInstance nodes.

You can read more about the door and pressure plate mechanisms in the Area guide.

Here we use a Dictionary, so the script can enable its matching NavigationMeshInstance when one door opens and disable the rest.

export var north_door_path: NodePath
export var east_door_path: NodePath

onready var _north_door = get_node(north_door_path)
onready var _east_door = get_node(east_door_path)
onready var _door_map := {
    _north_door: $NorthDoorOpen,
    _east_door: $EastDoorOpen,
}


func _ready() -> void:
    _door_map[_east_door].enabled = true


func activate() -> void:
    for door in _door_map:
        door.activate()
        _door_map[door].enabled = !_door_map[door].enabled

When our NavigationMeshInstance updates, the Navigation node uses whatever mesh is enabled when generating paths.

Grid-based navigation

Many games have pathfinding with restricted areas units can stand on, such as turn-based tactics games like XCOM.

If you want to restrict your movement to start and end on a grid, but you don’t mind if the movement isn’t locked to the grid, then Navigation is an excellent option.

The principle of using a Navigation for grid-based movement is the same as with enemy AI in the first example. Still, you need some extra steps to get the target position from a mouse click in 3D space and ensure the position is on the nearest valid grid position.

To get the position in 3D space from our mouse click, we project a ray from the camera position.

Now we have the world position from the raycast; we can pass it through the get_closest_point() function to get a position on the navigation mesh.

We need to offset the y-position to ensure the position aligns precisely with the mesh. This is due to the navigation mesh getting baked half the height of the NavigationMesh above the source mesh.

Finally, we set the position of a grid cursor, which is a spherical MeshInstance. The Vector3 snapped() function ensures the positions are always on our grid.

    if event is InputEventMouseMotion:
        var from := _camera.project_ray_origin(event.position)
        var to := from + _camera.project_ray_normal(event.position) * 9999.0
        var space := get_world().direct_space_state
        var result := space.intersect_ray(from, to)
        if result:
            var point = _navigation.get_closest_point(result["position"])
            # We need to negatively offset the point we get on the navigation
            # mesh by 2 x the height set on the Navigation Mesh Instance on the
            # y-axis for it to align exactly with the mesh.
            point -= Vector3(0.0, _navigation_mesh_instance.navmesh.get("cell/height") * 2.0, 0.0)
            _set_grid_cursor(point)
func _set_grid_cursor(position: Vector3) -> void:
    position = position.snapped(Vector3(1.0, 1.0, 1.0))
    _cursor.global_transform.origin = position

We listen for the user clicking and set the player destination to the cursor position.

    if event.is_action_pressed("shoot_3d"):
        _player.set_destination(_cursor.global_transform.origin)

The set_destination() function gets called in the player script, which starts the player processing.

func set_destination(position: Vector3):
    _path = _navigation.get_simple_path(global_transform.origin, position)
    set_physics_process(true)

After enabling _physics_process(), the player starts following the points in the path. Once at the destination, the player stops and _physics_process() turns off again.

func _physics_process(delta: float) -> void:
    var position_on_navigation_mesh = _navigation.get_closest_point(global_transform.origin)
    var final_destination := _path[_path.size() - 1]

    if (
        position_on_navigation_mesh.distance_squared_to(_path[0]) < path_tolerance
        and _path.size() > 1
    ):
        _path.remove(0)

    var direction: Vector3 = _path[0] - position_on_navigation_mesh

    direction.y = 0.0
    direction = direction.normalized()
    _orient_character_to_direction(direction, delta)

    _velocity = _velocity.linear_interpolate(direction * move_speed, acceleration * delta)
    _velocity = move_and_slide_with_snap(_velocity, _snap, Vector3.UP, true, 4, deg2rad(60))

Your questions

When should I use AStar?

You can get more robust results and control using the AStar algorithm with more manual work. If you’re struggling with the unpredictable and imprecise nature of Navigation in Godot 3.x, it’s worth considering implementing the pathfinding yourself using AStar. You can read the Godot Docs on AStar here.

How can I see my Navigation shapes?

Godot has a handy option in the debug dropdown. The Visible Navigation checkmark makes all NavigationMeshes visible in-game when enabled.

Can I create my NavigationMesh in code?

Yes. To create a NavigationMesh from code, you need to call set_vertices() and add_polygon() or create_from_mesh() and manually add the NavigationMesh with the navmesh_add() function. Note that when doing this, you don’t need a NavigationMeshInstance node.

Note: A <span class="godot-icon-class"><svg height="16" viewBox="0 0 16 16" width="16" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="m3 1a2 2 0 0 0 -2 2 2 2 0 0 0 1 1.7305v6.541a2 2 0 0 0 -1 1.7285 2 2 0 0 0 2 2 2 2 0 0 0 1.7305-1h2.5078l.75-2h-3.2598a2 2 0 0 0 -.72852-.73047v-5.8555l4.6973 4.6973.77148-2.0566-4.0547-4.0547h5.8574a2 2 0 0 0 .72852.73047v.27148a2.0002 2.0002 0 0 1 .023438 0 2.0002 2.0002 0 0 1 1.8496 1.2969l.12695.33789v-1.9082a2 2 0 0 0 1-1.7285 2 2 0 0 0 -2-2 2 2 0 0 0 -1.7305 1h-6.541a2 2 0 0 0 -1.7285-1zm9 6-3 8 3-2 3 2z" fill="#ffd684"/></svg>NavigationMesh</span> added via code does not appear in the debug view mentioned above.

Here is a simple example of adding a single three-sided polygon as a NavigationMesh.

extends Navigation


func _ready() -> void:
    var nav_mesh := NavigationMesh.new()
    var vertices := PoolVector3Array([Vector3(-1.0, 0.5, 1.0), Vector3(1.0, 0.5, 1.0), Vector3(0.0, 0.5, -1.0)])
    var polygon := PoolIntArray([0, 1, 2])
    nav_mesh.set_vertices(vertices)
    nav_mesh.add_polygon(polygon)
    navmesh_add(nav_mesh, Transform.IDENTITY)

Is it possible to use Navigation for flying pathfinding?

No. The navigation paths you get back from the Navigation system are based on mesh shapes and thus only know how to get from one point on a mesh to another point on the mesh.
